    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Huntington disease is an autosomal dominant genetic disorder affecting approximately 1 in 15000 Australian population. The disease affects males and females equally and is found in all ethnic groups but is among people of European descent. Symptoms often start between 30 and 50 years of age and can include involuntary muscle movements (irregular, jerky and uncoordinated), slurred speech and difficulties with swallowing, disruptions to thought processes (short term memory loss, difficulty with making decisions, lack of motivation, reduced insight and awareness of social boundaries), unsteadiness and falls, difficulty with emotional control, frustration, agitation and mood swings, and depression and anxiety. HD progresses slowly; after developing the first symptoms, affected people usually live 15 to 20 years. According to Australian national guideline in concordance with WHO, eligibility criteria for genetic testing are: the age of the individual is at least 18 years AND there is at least one blood-relative with definite diagnosis of HD in the pedigree. This means no genetic testing for HD is performed on request of a person, or the carers (e.g. parents) of a person under the age of 18 years. Based on the guideline, genetic testing requested by the mother should not be performed for this girl until the age of 18. On the other hand, her very young age excludes her from genetic counselling (not testing) for her. She is too young to understand and handle the given information or handle the social and emotional ramifications.`,
