    explanation: `Drawing intersecting pentagons assesses constructional praxis, which requires three-dimensional spatial manipulation. This is a task of the non-dominant (right) parietal lobe. Lesions of the non-dominant parietal lobe lead to constructional apraxia, characterized by inability to copy or draw complex figures despite intact motor and sensory function. The dominant parietal lobe is involved in language and calculation. The temporal lobe is involved in memory and language processing. The temporoparietal region is involved in language comprehension. The frontal lobe is involved in executive function, motor control, and speech production (Broca's area).`,
