    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Ulnar nerve injury can cause weakness of most intrinsic hand muscles while sparing the thenar eminence. The ulnar nerve innervates all interosseous muscles, the 3rd and 4th lumbrical muscles, and muscles in the hypothenar eminence. While ulnar nerve injuries affect the function of these muscles, thenar eminence muscles are spared because they are supplied by the median nerve. Median nerve injuries affect thenar muscles (flexor pollicis brevis, abductor pollicis brevis, and opponens pollicis). Radial nerve supplies muscles in the posterior compartment of the forearm but no small hand muscles. Anterior interosseous nerve is a motor branch of the median nerve supplying forearm muscles (flexor pollicis longus, flexor digitorum profundus 2nd and 3rd fingers, and pronator quadratus), not hand muscles. Posterior interosseous nerve is a branch of the radial nerve supplying posterior forearm muscles, not hand muscles.`,
