    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Low vitamin D level from reduced sun exposure is a known risk factor for developing multiple sclerosis. The disease commonly affects women aged 20 to 40 years, especially white people of Northern European descent. The prevalence of this disease is more common in locations that are further away from the equator. Chronic smoking (option B) has been noted to be a factor in the development of multiple sclerosis, although not to a degree as significant as low vitamin D levels. Further studies are required in order to investigate the relationship between smoking and MS. Vitamin D levels are directly correlated to a person's sun exposure. Having prolonged sun exposure (option C) is found to decrease the chances of developing MS. Fifteen minutes of daily sun exposure has been shown to reduce the severity of symptoms as well. Increased alcohol intake (option D) has not been found to be linked with the development of multiple sclerosis, however, it remains a potential trigger for increased severity of symptoms. Caffeine intake (option E) has been shown to have a protective effect against multiple sclerosis and is not considered a risk factor.`,
    reference: "amc",
    difficulty: "medium",
