    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `The scenario describes a cut in the thenar area of this child. The clinical presentation of weakness of all ankle movements (dorsiflexion, plantar flexion, eversion, and inversion), numbness over the dorsum and sole of the foot and lateral aspect of the leg, and absent ankle jerk is consistent with left sciatic nerve injury. The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the body and is commonly injured during hip replacement surgery. The sciatic nerve divides into the tibial and common peroneal nerves. Injury to the sciatic nerve results in weakness of all ankle movements and sensory loss over the foot and lateral leg. The ankle jerk (Achilles reflex) is mediated by the S1 and S2 nerve roots via the tibial nerve, which is a branch of the sciatic nerve. Therefore, sciatic nerve injury results in an absent ankle jerk.`,
