    explanation: `Option D is correct. Hypertension is the most important preventable risk factor for CVA, accounting for 50% of cases. All patients should receive blood pressure lowering therapy after stroke or TIA, regardless of their blood pressure (not option C). Antiplatelet therapy is the standard for ischemic stroke/TIA, but in the presence of AF, aspirin (option E) will not provide adequate protection against thromboembolism. Warfarin is the standard of care in patients with CVA in the setting of AF and is preferred over aspirin or other antiplatelet agents. The patient has 50% stenosis in the right and 40% stenosis in the left carotid arteries. Current guidelines recommend carotid endarterectomy (CEA) for non-disabling carotid artery territory ischemic stroke or TIA with ipsilateral carotid stenosis measured at 70-99% if surgery can be performed by a specialist surgeon with <5% perioperative mortality/morbidity, or stenoses of 50-69% in selected patients with <3% risk of perioperative mortality/morbidity. Since the stenoses are below these thresholds, CEA is not recommended (option A). Smoking cessation (option B) is important but not as critical as warfarin therapy at this stage.`,
