    subtopic: "Acute urinary retention - post-catheterization management",
    stem: `Tom, 67 years old, presents to your GP clinic with complaint of urinary retention since this morning. He mentions that he has had difficulty starting voiding and terminal dribbling. On examination, he is in mild distress. All his vital signs including the temperature are within normal limits. On abdominal examination, a slightly tender dull mass is felt up to 2-finger breadth above his symphysis pubis. A digital rectal exam (DRE) reveals an enlarged prostate with normal consistency, no nodularity and a palpable median sulcus. You insert a urinary catheter for immediate relief of symptoms. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?`,
