    id: "neuro-amedex-0112",
    topic: "Neurology",
    subtopic: "Nephrolithiasis",
    stem: `A 70-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a complaint of intermittent loin pain for the past 48 hours. On examination, he is afebrile and there is no tenderness over the loin, flank or costovertebral angle. A urine test shows 3+ hematuria with negativity for protein and nitrite. Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Abdominal X-ray` },
      { label: "B", text: `Intravenous pyelogram (IVP)` },
      { label: "C", text: `Abdominal CT scan` },
      { label: "D", text: `Retrograde pyelography` },
      { label: "E", text: `Urine culture` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `The scenario is highly suggestive of kidney stone(s) (nephrolithiasis) as the most likely diagnosis. Nephrolithiasis affects one in 10 persons in Australia. Although most stones pass spontaneously, some conditions require intervention. These conditions include: continuous pain, renal impairment, and urinary tract infections. For every patient presenting with a clinical picture suggestive of urinary stones, investigations should be considered to determine the location, number and size of the stone(s) that influence its likelihood of spontaneous passage. A non-contrast CT scan of the abdomen for assessment of the kidneys, ureters, and bladder (CT-KUB) is the gold-standard investigation. CT-KUB has a sensitivity and specificity of approximately 100% for evaluating urinary stones irrespective of stone type. It also provides an opportunity for an alternative diagnosis if no stone(s) are visualized. NOTE - CT is the gold standard for the diagnosis of ureteric calculi. However, due to concerns about ionising radiation in this cohort of patients who have a high incidence of recurrent disease and the fact that the vast majority of ureteric stones pass without the need for intervention, CT in the emergency department rarely alters immediate management. There is a trend towards a more discriminate use of CT of the kidneys, ureters and urinary bladder (KUB) in patients with clinical uncomplicated acute renal colic, particularly in young female patients, in whom there is a relatively high incidence of negative CT examinations, and in whom radiation is more of an issue. Therefore, it has been suggested by several authors, including the European Association of Urology, that ultrasound (US) should be considered the primary imaging technique. It is a reproducible, non-invasive and non-expensive imaging technique, achieving accurate diagnosis in most cases without the need for radiation. A recent study comparing 'point-of-care' US, US performed in the radiology department, and CT showed that the initial US was associated with lower cumulative ionising radiation doses but no other significant difference in outcomes. It is, therefore, apparent that despite the inferior sensitivity of the US, the outcome is the same whether CT or US is used for imaging. If KUB US was an option, it would be the correct answer. It is important to note that an additional KUB plain film (x-ray) should be obtained at the same presentation. If the stone is visible on plain KUB, this can be used for follow-up imaging with a lower radiation dose. Only calcium-containing stones are visible on plain KUB X-ray, and this information also has implications for stone management. Option A: As mentioned above, a KUB x-ray is performed to reduce the radiation exposure associated with CT scanning if the stone is visualized. Otherwise, this modality is not sensitive enough to establish a diagnosis. Option B: Intravenous pyelogram (IVP) is used rarely in the diagnosis of ureteric colic due to the high sensitivity and specificity of non-contrast CT KUB. However, a contrast study (CT urogram) may sometimes be helpful for treatment planning purposes. Retrograde pyelography (option C) serves the same purpose as IVP, but the contrast material is pushed up through a urinary catheter. This test has no role in the evaluation of patients with renal colic. Option E: This patient has no signs, symptoms, or dipstick urine exam findings suggestive of urinary tract infection. If that was the case, a urine culture and sensitivity would have been indicated for further management.`,
