    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The photograph shows an ultrasonographic view of the right testis, which shows a lesion. The lesion is a combination of cystic and solid structures. Until proven otherwise, a testicular lump in a young man is testicular cancer. When testicular cancer is suspected on ultrasound, the next best step is always obtaining a blood sample for serum tumour markers. Three serum tumour markers have established roles in patients with suspected testicular cancer: (1) alpha-fetoprotein (AFP), (2) the beta subunit of human chorionic gonadotropin (beta-hCG), and (3) lactate dehydrogenase (LDH). Tumour markers differ by histological subtype of testicular malignancies. In pure seminoma testicular cancers, AFP is never elevated and beta-hCG is elevated in fewer than 20% of patients. In other histological subtypes, AFP and beta-hCG are elevated in 85% of patients. Of the options, only measuring serum AFP can be correct as the next best step in management. However, the best option would recommend both AFP and beta-hCG. Option A: No man with a testicular lump can be reassured unless thorough investigations exclude testicular malignancies. Option C: CEA is not a tumour marker for testicular cancer. Option D and E: Tumor marker studies and imaging studies should be performed prior to surgical management. If surgery is planned, a trans-inguinal approach should be considered, as there is a risk of tumour spread and scrotal seeding when the testis is reached through the scrotum.`,
    reference: "amc",
