    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Hematuria may be seen in a variety of situations including, but not limited to: Infections, Renal stones, Glomerulonephritis, Urinary tract malignancies, Trauma. Infections are the most common cause of hematuria in both symptomatic and asymptomatic patients. For this reason, the next best step in the management of every patient with hematuria would be a urine analysis and culture. Once urine culture is negative and renal stones are excluded using ultrasound (option A) (the best initial test) or spiral CT (option B) (the most accurate test), urologic malignancies (mostly cancer of the bladder) should be considered and ruled out. Cystoscopy (option C) is used when direct visualization of a bladder lesion is indicated, such as in the assessment of a malignant bladder tumour. It is not indicated at this stage. With other modalities such as CT scans, IVP (option E) is not used that often anymore.`,
