    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `The scenario is a typical case of stress urinary incontinence. Stress incontinence is the most common cause of urinary incontinence in younger women and the second most common cause in older women (after mixed incontinence), and occurs when an increase in intraabdominal pressure overcomes sphincter closure mechanisms in the absence of a bladder contraction. Pelvic floor muscle exercise is the initial therapy in women with stress and mixed incontinence, and it is also useful, in combination with bladder training, for women with urge incontinence. If pelvic floor muscle training fails, the mainstay of treatment is surgery. Surgery has high cure rates for stress urinary incontinence, even in elderly women. A vaginal or abdominal approach can be used for surgical treatment. Vaginal procedures include a mid-urethral sling (insertion of a tension-free vaginal tape under the urethra), bladder neck sling (suspension), or injection of urethral bulking agents. Burch's retropubic colposuspension is an abdominal procedure for stress urinary incontinence and is a more invasive procedure compared with other surgical methods. NOTE - Insertion of a tension-free vaginal tape (mid-urethral sling) was the preferred correct answer if among options. This procedure is minimally invasive and has become the gold standard for surgical treatment of stress urinary incontinence.`,
